# Git Push from Cursor

**Repo:** https://github.com/PattyFrank/patientpartner-master

## Why Agent Push Fails

The Cursor agent runs commands in a non-interactive sandbox. `git push` requires GitHub credentials, which cannot be entered there. The agent can stage, commit, and configure remotes—but **you must run push yourself**.

## How to Push from Cursor

### Option 1: Cursor Source Control (recommended)

1. **Open Source Control:** `Ctrl+Shift+G` (or `Cmd+Shift+G` on Mac)
2. **Commit** any changes if needed (stage, write message, commit)
3. **Push:** Click the `...` menu → **Push**, or click the sync icon if it shows push/pull

Uses your system Git credentials. If prompted, enter GitHub username and a [Personal Access Token](https://github.com/settings/tokens) (not your password).

### Option 2: Cursor Terminal

1. **Open Terminal:** `` Ctrl+` `` (or View → Terminal)
2. Run:
   ```bash
   cd ~/projects/patientpartner-master
   git push origin main
   ```
3. Enter credentials if prompted (username + PAT)

### Option 3: One-Time Auth Setup (no more prompts)

**macOS Keychain:**
```bash
git config --global credential.helper osxkeychain
```
Then run `git push` once from Cursor's Terminal—enter your GitHub username and a PAT when prompted. Future pushes will use stored credentials.

**SSH (no prompts):**
```bash
# 1. Generate key if needed: ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"
# 2. Add to GitHub: https://github.com/settings/keys
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:PattyFrank/patientpartner-master.git
git push origin main
```

## After Agent Makes Changes

When the agent commits changes, run push via Source Control or Terminal. The agent cannot complete the push for you.
